<p>but it would scarcely be the place to take a lady friend to.<br/>Cairo at night time presents a very pretty sight with its crowded streets &amp; different races of people. When first we landed in Cairo in 1914. English speaking people were pretty rare (French Italian, Greek, &amp; Arabic were the most popular languages) but when we left Cairo in 1916 practically everyone could speak a little English, its marvellous how it spread so quickly, due no doubt to the thousands of Australian NZ &amp; English troops who thronged the streets, there are 2 very fine hotels there the "Continental" &amp; "Shepherds" both cater for the wealthy</p>
